<DocsPage
  title="Hook System"
  section="Architecture"
  description="How session data is captured from AI coding tools."
>
  <p>
    The SessionEnd hook is the data collection layer of Primer. It runs automatically at the end
    of each Claude Code, Codex CLI, or Gemini CLI session, extracts session metadata from the
    transcript, and uploads it to your Primer server.
  </p>

  <h2>How It Works</h2>

  <p>When a Claude Code session ends, the hook:</p>

  <ol>
    <li>Reads the session transcript (a JSONL file in <code>~/.claude/projects/</code>)</li>
    <li>Parses messages, token counts, tool calls, model names, and session metadata</li>
    <li>Loads facets from <code>~/.claude/usage-data/facets/</code> if available</li>
    <li>POSTs the extracted data to <code>/api/v1/ingest/session</code></li>
    <li>Fails silently if the server is unreachable (sessions can be synced later via MCP)</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Installation</h2>

  <p>First, make sure you have a Primer engineer account and API key:</p>

  <pre><code>curl -X POST http://localhost:8000/api/v1/engineers \
  -H "x-admin-key: primer-admin-dev-key" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '&#123;"name": "Your Name", "email": "you@example.com"&#125;'
# Save the api_key from the response</code></pre>

  <p>Set your environment variables and install:</p>

  <pre><code>export PRIMER_SERVER_URL=http://your-primer-server:8000
export PRIMER_API_KEY=primer_...
python scripts/install_hook.py</code></pre>

  <p>
    Or use the CLI: <code>primer hook install</code>
  </p>

  <h3>What Gets Installed</h3>

  <p>
    The installer adds a <code>SessionEnd</code> hook to <code>~/.claude/settings.json</code>:
  </p>

  <pre><code>&#123;
  "hooks": &#123;
    "SessionEnd": [
      &#123;
        "matcher": "",
        "hooks": [
          &#123;
            "type": "command",
            "command": "python -m primer.hook.extractor"
          &#125;
        ]
      &#125;
    ]
  &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>

  <h2>Verifying the Hook</h2>

  <p>Check that the hook is registered:</p>

  <pre><code>cat ~/.claude/settings.json | python -m json.tool</code></pre>

  <p>After completing a Claude Code session, verify it was uploaded:</p>

  <pre><code>curl http://localhost:8000/api/v1/sessions \
  -H "x-admin-key: primer-admin-dev-key" | python -m json.tool</code></pre>

  <h2>What Data Is Extracted</h2>

  <p>The extractor parses the JSONL transcript and captures:</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Field</th><th>Source</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Session ID, start/end times</td><td>Transcript metadata</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Message counts (user, assistant, total)</td><td>Transcript messages</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Input/output/cache tokens</td><td>Usage fields in messages</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tool call counts (per tool)</td><td>Tool use blocks</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Model names and per-model token usage</td><td>Message metadata</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Project path, git branch</td><td>Session environment</td></tr>
      <tr><td>First prompt, session summary</td><td>Message content</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Permission mode, end reason</td><td>Session metadata</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Agent type and version</td><td>Session metadata</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Multi-Agent Support</h2>

  <p>
    Primer supports multiple AI coding tools through agent-specific extractors. The hook
    automatically detects the agent type and uses the appropriate extraction logic:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Claude Code</strong> — JSONL transcript with tool use blocks</li>
    <li><strong>Codex CLI</strong> — OpenAI-compatible conversation format</li>
    <li><strong>Gemini CLI</strong> — Gemini conversation format</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    All agents upload to the same ingest endpoint. The <code>agent_type</code> field on each
    session identifies the source.
  </p>

  <h2>Offline Sync</h2>

  <p>
    If the Primer server is unreachable when a session ends, the hook fails silently without
    disrupting your workflow. You can sync missed sessions later using the MCP sidecar:
  </p>

  <pre><code># In Claude Code, call the sync MCP tool
# Or directly via CLI:
python -m primer.mcp.server  # Then call the sync tool</code></pre>

  <h2>Uninstalling</h2>

  <pre><code>python scripts/install_hook.py --uninstall
# Or:
primer hook uninstall</code></pre>

  <p>
    This removes the <code>SessionEnd</code> entry from <code>~/.claude/settings.json</code>.
    Your existing session data on the server is not affected.
  </p>
</DocsPage>
